WEBVTT

00:03.621 --> 00:08.824
♪ ♪

00:18.469 --> 00:22.271
♪ ♪

00:22.406 --> 00:25.040
WILL SMITH: Where is home?

00:32.116 --> 00:34.349
Is it where you were born?

00:34.418 --> 00:40.155
(alarm clock beeping)

00:45.129 --> 00:47.663
Where you were raised?

00:50.834 --> 00:53.469
Or where you are now?

00:55.406 --> 00:57.873
Is it somewhere you live?

01:01.111 --> 01:03.445
Somewhere you left?

01:06.717 --> 01:10.219
Somewhere that shaped you?

01:15.926 --> 01:19.695
If you really wanna know, you
need to leave them all behind.

01:24.935 --> 01:29.103
Someone who knows that it's
like to really leave home is

01:29.940 --> 01:34.176
Peggy Whitson, NASA's most
experienced astronaut.

01:36.914 --> 01:39.214
Not that you'd know it
if you ever met her.

01:39.416 --> 01:41.350
PEGGY: Well I hate
talking about the records,

01:41.352 --> 01:43.351
but I do have few.

01:43.721 --> 01:46.288
WILL SMITH: That folks is the
understatement of the year.

01:47.224 --> 01:51.627
How about we start with
most time in space for
any US astronaut.

01:52.730 --> 01:54.763
-Which is 665 days.

01:55.232 --> 01:56.832
WILL SMITH: Think about
that for a second,

01:56.901 --> 01:59.201
that's a round trip to Mars.

01:59.837 --> 02:01.236
(laughs).

02:01.305 --> 02:04.505
Then there's the longest
single space flight for any

02:04.542 --> 02:05.707
woman in the world.

02:05.743 --> 02:07.242
-Oh, that's right, yeah.

02:07.244 --> 02:08.810
WILL SMITH: And that's
just for starters.

02:08.813 --> 02:13.248
-Ten space walks, first female
Commander and I can't remember

02:13.617 --> 02:17.219
the other, oh, I know oldest
astronaut, female astronaut,

02:18.422 --> 02:20.656
not a record I
was looking for.

02:23.994 --> 02:26.395
The press seemed to
point that one out a lot.

02:27.965 --> 02:30.165
WILL SMITH: Not bad for
a farm girl from Iowa!

02:35.406 --> 02:40.843
Eight astronauts, Chris,
Nicole, Jeff, May, Jerry,

02:42.213 --> 02:46.415
Mike, Leland and
then there's Peggy.

02:47.751 --> 02:50.919
Each one of them is different,
they come from different places,

02:51.054 --> 02:55.157
they have different
stories to tell but they were
all changed by one thing...

02:56.026 --> 02:58.493
Going into space.

02:58.829 --> 03:01.963
It's called the Overview
Effect and if you could see

03:02.032 --> 03:04.233
what they've seen,
you'd feel it too.

03:16.380 --> 03:21.016
♪ ♪

03:26.323 --> 03:29.625
Most of us leave
home every day.

03:34.698 --> 03:37.566
We go to work without
a second thought.

03:48.479 --> 03:52.381
But just imagine
if your work place
overlooks the planet

03:55.118 --> 03:59.521
then that morning
commute becomes a little
bit more challenging.

04:03.060 --> 04:05.928
-We launch from
Baikonur, Kazakhstan.

04:07.531 --> 04:10.699
It was actually the same
launch pad that Yuri Gagarin
launched from.

04:22.880 --> 04:25.781
It's a fast trip
to get to space.

04:28.252 --> 04:30.185
Better than any car
you've ever been in,

04:30.254 --> 04:33.088
better than any acceleration
you've ever experienced.

04:33.557 --> 04:36.591
It feels good to
be going fast.

04:37.127 --> 04:40.528
Eight and a half minutes
after leaving the launchpad

04:40.564 --> 04:43.432
we are in orbit.

04:45.069 --> 04:47.135
WILL SMITH: The
international space station

04:47.137 --> 04:50.538
is 250 miles above the planet.

04:51.375 --> 04:53.675
But it is a million
miles away from the place

04:53.744 --> 04:55.978
Peggy first called home.

05:05.756 --> 05:11.059
♪ ♪

05:14.297 --> 05:16.598
-Growing up on a farm I
think was actually a really

05:16.600 --> 05:20.568
good experience for me,
it taught me a lot of

05:20.604 --> 05:22.804
dedication and hard work.

05:28.712 --> 05:31.146
-She says she'd
like to go to Mars.

05:34.752 --> 05:39.253
-My parents have lived on
the same farm for fifty,

05:39.456 --> 05:42.190
almost sixty years.

05:44.128 --> 05:46.928
My mom was
incredibly supportive.

05:46.930 --> 05:50.598
At one time I was telling my
sister I wanted to be a pilot

05:50.634 --> 05:53.868
and learn to fly and she's
like, "You can't be a pilot,

05:53.937 --> 05:57.472
you can only be a stewardess."
and my mom told her,

05:57.541 --> 06:00.108
"No, you can be anything
you want to be!"

06:00.377 --> 06:03.611
-I think there's two Peggy's,
the one that comes here and

06:03.680 --> 06:06.448
the one that goes there
are different people.

06:14.224 --> 06:16.757
WILL SMITH: An astronaut will
have trained for at least

06:16.794 --> 06:19.160
three years for a mission.

06:19.229 --> 06:22.430
Every moment in space is
scheduled with experiments to

06:22.466 --> 06:24.432
run and tasks to complete.

06:25.302 --> 06:28.904
But the first thing they wanna
do is exactly what we do when

06:29.039 --> 06:31.540
we go somewhere new,
check out the view.

06:37.147 --> 06:40.181
Going into space is like
I live my whole life in a

06:40.250 --> 06:43.151
semi-dark room and somebody
flipped on the lights.

06:52.529 --> 06:57.532
♪ ♪

06:59.636 --> 07:02.671
The earth just seems
to glow, it's so beautiful.

07:11.081 --> 07:13.014
♪ ♪

07:13.150 --> 07:15.016
CHRIS: When I first
went to space,

07:15.585 --> 07:19.020
the first thing I wanted to
do was pop off my helmet,

07:19.489 --> 07:22.157
unstrap out of my chair, float
up weightless and go to the

07:22.292 --> 07:24.292
window and see the world.

07:25.629 --> 07:29.564
NICOLE: What we see
with our eyes, what
we then I think feel

07:29.566 --> 07:32.901
through our heart says
your experiencing it is,

07:33.137 --> 07:35.370
it's beyond imagination.

07:38.175 --> 07:40.808
LELAND: It is just so
stunningly beautiful it almost

07:41.278 --> 07:44.579
makes you, you, you wanna
find new words to describe

07:44.615 --> 07:48.750
the emotion that
you're feeling because it
affects you so powerfully.

07:52.322 --> 07:57.993
MIKE: This is something
that human eyes are not
supposed to see.

07:57.995 --> 07:59.728
WILL SMITH: Looking out
the window may not be the

07:59.730 --> 08:03.664
highest mission priority...

08:04.134 --> 08:08.103
but it has a lasting
impact on all astronauts.

08:10.107 --> 08:13.575
It changes how they think
about where they're from.

08:19.149 --> 08:22.384
PEGGY: The town closest
to my parents farm
is Beaconsfield, Iowa.

08:23.653 --> 08:26.688
When I was growing up it
had like 32 people in it and

08:26.690 --> 08:30.125
I think it's down to
eleven'ish now so it's
a pretty small town.

08:34.698 --> 08:38.499
WILL SMITH: Beaconsfield maybe
the smallest town in Iowa but

08:38.569 --> 08:41.870
it's a place full
of amazing stories,

08:43.173 --> 08:45.973
amazing transformations.

08:46.543 --> 08:50.145
-Growing up in Iowa there's
all kinds of life around...

08:53.283 --> 08:55.716
and when somebody says
the word "butterfly"
you always think

08:55.752 --> 08:57.785
of the Monarch butterfly
because it's the most

08:57.854 --> 09:00.222
distinctive one that
I saw growing up.

09:03.260 --> 09:04.859
AUBREE: This one's
a pretty good one.

09:04.861 --> 09:06.928
-It's big!

09:08.966 --> 09:11.700
-They feel like soft and
gooey at the same time.

09:12.269 --> 09:14.002
-I know!

09:15.005 --> 09:17.906
-The spring and summer there
are lots of caterpillars,

09:19.610 --> 09:23.311
it's easy to find them because
they're only on the milkweed.

09:25.282 --> 09:27.816
-It's always interesting to
see the caterpillars crawling

09:27.818 --> 09:31.186
around and recognize
that someday that's
gonna become a butterfly.

09:34.024 --> 09:36.825
-You like to move
around a lot don't you.

09:38.328 --> 09:41.496
WILL SMITH:
We all know that caterpillars
turn into butterflies...

09:43.733 --> 09:46.634
but does it make it
any less wondrous?

09:47.404 --> 09:50.572
It's as extraordinary
as a farm girl from Iowa

09:50.574 --> 09:53.875
transforming into
an astronaut.

10:01.785 --> 10:04.452
♪ ♪

10:04.521 --> 10:10.692
The Monarch butterfly's
caterpillar is
nature's shape shifter supreme.

10:20.603 --> 10:25.540
-When the caterpillar
is inside the chrysalis
it dissolves and it

10:25.609 --> 10:27.942
turns into goo...

10:33.483 --> 10:36.618
And then the good
turns into a butterfly.

10:45.729 --> 10:52.200
♪ ♪

11:01.845 --> 11:03.845
♪ ♪

11:03.847 --> 11:07.048
WILL SMITH: Caterpillars
don't know much of the
world beyond a milkweed plant

11:08.985 --> 11:11.953
but once a butterfly
it's cleared for takeoff.

11:22.199 --> 11:25.834
And from up high it gains a
new perspective on the world.

11:35.679 --> 11:41.582
♪ ♪

11:41.818 --> 11:45.887
Astronauts change
when they leave earth.

11:49.025 --> 11:52.293
They undergo a metamorphosis.

11:57.334 --> 12:01.703
Home is no longer a town,
it's something much bigger.

12:04.541 --> 12:07.107
NICOLE: I think the
opportunity to kind of live in

12:07.144 --> 12:10.245
space has allowed
me to look at things a

12:10.247 --> 12:11.913
little bit differently.

12:12.048 --> 12:14.048
It really opens up
a new perspective.

12:15.552 --> 12:18.319
MIKE: I don't think
about the city I live
in or where I'm from,

12:18.721 --> 12:22.123
I think about home
and home is our whole
planet or whole earth,

12:22.692 --> 12:25.727
it's one home for all of us.

12:26.563 --> 12:29.464
-As I've grown up and gone
to college and gone to graduate

12:29.466 --> 12:33.435
school home has expanded
from Iowa to Texas to the

12:33.570 --> 12:37.538
United States and since
being in space home is

12:37.574 --> 12:39.274
actually planet Earth!

12:48.785 --> 12:53.555
♪ ♪

13:00.697 --> 13:02.697
-Look!

13:06.536 --> 13:08.603
-Here she comes!

13:13.176 --> 13:16.244
WILL SMITH: There she is.

13:20.783 --> 13:25.487
-17,500 miles an hour,
fast moving star.

13:27.323 --> 13:29.891
-That's your daughter
up there, isn't it?

13:34.598 --> 13:38.600
There's lot of stars
out there tonight but she's
the only one that's moving.

13:41.104 --> 13:45.106
Bye Peggy, hurry home.

13:49.546 --> 13:52.981
WILL SMITH: Astronauts don't
spend all their free time at

13:52.983 --> 13:57.018
the window looking at earth,
after all they're explorers so

13:58.154 --> 14:00.554
it's only natural for
them to turn the other way

14:00.590 --> 14:02.690
towards the
far reaches of space.

14:04.294 --> 14:06.828
They set their sights
on what's out there.

14:08.164 --> 14:12.867
Thing is,
that big window on the
ISS only points one way,

14:14.037 --> 14:15.904
down to earth.

14:16.039 --> 14:19.707
To see the cosmos you
have to step outside!

14:26.166 --> 14:28.733
WILL SMITH: You'd think when
you're in space you'd have

14:28.735 --> 14:32.337
lots of it, you've probably
got more room in your back

14:32.339 --> 14:34.739
yard than the astronauts
have on the ISS.

14:36.142 --> 14:39.544
It is cramped up there.

14:39.979 --> 14:43.181
You don't really experience
space until you walk in it!

14:49.322 --> 14:52.023
PEGGY: Going for a walk
it's not a trivial process,

14:52.425 --> 14:54.792
it takes a lot of
work and preparation.

14:54.794 --> 14:59.330
But, everyone wants
to do it because oh my gosh
the view is phenomenal!

15:05.272 --> 15:08.239
WILL SMITH: On a
spacewalk it's just you!

15:08.574 --> 15:09.974
Floating!

15:10.043 --> 15:12.844
No up, no down.

15:12.979 --> 15:16.881
Turn one way a 250 mile
drop back to earth,

15:18.318 --> 15:22.020
the other an endless
expanse of unblinking stars.

15:23.156 --> 15:25.723
The main thing astronauts
remember though is not the

15:25.825 --> 15:28.192
stars but the black.

15:30.664 --> 15:34.165
Looking into that
void makes astronauts
ask the same question,

15:35.168 --> 15:38.236
"Is there anybody out there?"

15:39.539 --> 15:42.673
MAE: To say that there's no
life elsewhere in the universe

15:42.676 --> 15:44.742
is a real stretch.

15:45.178 --> 15:46.677
JERRY: You know
mathematics doesn't lie,

15:46.746 --> 15:49.880
probability doesn't lie and
when you look at these numbers

15:50.883 --> 15:54.285
surely there has to be
some other life out there.

15:54.620 --> 15:57.822
-There's got to be other life
out there, there has to be.

15:58.091 --> 16:00.892
It's just a matter of whether
we can find it or not.

16:09.069 --> 16:12.035
WILL SMITH: To find out if
we have neighbors you need a

16:12.072 --> 16:17.241
telescope and I'm
talking big, really big!

16:27.387 --> 16:32.757
♪ ♪

17:11.097 --> 17:14.164
WILL SMITH:
This dish is a giant ear,

17:14.968 --> 17:17.835
listening to radio waves
coming from deep space.

18:37.784 --> 18:40.184
WILL SMITH: There are
literally billions of strange

18:40.253 --> 18:44.222
rocks out there but
so far not a whisper
from any of them.

18:46.059 --> 18:47.692
Nada!

18:57.670 --> 19:00.271
WILL SMITH: So
where is everybody?

19:00.406 --> 19:02.406
Well...

19:02.876 --> 19:05.743
it's about 250 miles
from earth to the

19:05.878 --> 19:07.979
international space station,

19:10.283 --> 19:12.416
250,000 miles to the moon.

19:13.620 --> 19:15.720
Long way right?

19:16.889 --> 19:19.089
Baby steps!

19:19.526 --> 19:22.293
Saturn, 700 million miles.

19:25.098 --> 19:28.266
Edge of the solar system,
over nine trillion.

19:29.602 --> 19:33.704
Our nearest start, four
and a quarter light years.

19:35.074 --> 19:37.708
Aboard our fastest
spacecraft it will take

19:37.744 --> 19:42.547
17,000 years to
get there and that's just
our next-door neighbor!

19:46.419 --> 19:49.787
Travelling beyond, through
our galaxy to the edge of the

19:49.922 --> 19:53.991
Milky Way we're talking
25,000 light years!

19:57.129 --> 19:59.997
And our galaxy is
just one of trillions!

20:02.335 --> 20:06.070
So life elsewhere
might just be a very,

20:06.172 --> 20:09.840
very long way away...

20:10.343 --> 20:12.476
And there's another thing,

20:12.512 --> 20:16.947
any aliens out there might
not be able to say "hello"

20:16.950 --> 20:20.985
because they might not have
a mouth or even a brain.

21:26.319 --> 21:28.819
WILL SMITH: These jellyfish
have found a way to capture

21:28.855 --> 21:31.088
energy from sunlight.

21:44.404 --> 21:48.439
WILL SMITH: If life exists
elsewhere it will need energy,

21:48.841 --> 21:52.376
probably from a sun and
water just like on earth.

21:54.781 --> 21:58.381
But like these jellyfish most
creatures on our planet are

21:58.418 --> 22:02.353
not intelligent, they
never ask to phone home!

22:24.544 --> 22:27.077
JERRY: There's probably life
out there in the universe but

22:27.146 --> 22:32.016
to find intelligent life,
those odds go way, way,
way down.

22:32.752 --> 22:34.952
JEFF: We don't know for
sure that we're alone but

22:34.954 --> 22:37.822
psychologically,
spiritually, culturally we

22:37.957 --> 22:40.424
definitely are alone.

22:41.093 --> 22:43.494
NICOLE: As far as we know
we're the only ones like us.

22:45.565 --> 22:48.933
WILL SMITH: Space is
almost entirely nothing.

22:50.770 --> 22:54.939
Adrift in that empty void
it's easy to feel completely

22:56.242 --> 22:58.308
and utterly alone.

22:58.578 --> 23:02.079
That's when earth starts
to look really good.

23:09.622 --> 23:12.689
WILL SMITH: Down here we
see infinite blue skies and

23:13.192 --> 23:15.092
life all around us.

23:15.161 --> 23:16.827
For astronauts it's different.

23:17.697 --> 23:20.164
Everywhere they
look is barren,

23:20.166 --> 23:23.801
life exists in just a
single, solitary oasis.

23:27.406 --> 23:30.875
The more they look
at it, the more they
appreciate the earth.

23:33.279 --> 23:37.581
They begin to understand the
shear interconnectedness of

23:37.617 --> 23:40.518
the natural world.

23:40.820 --> 23:44.388
The earth begins to reveal
patterns, connections,

23:45.391 --> 23:47.691
seasons, systems and cycles.

23:49.862 --> 23:52.630
PEGGY: It really is
enlightening to me how complex

23:52.765 --> 23:55.666
even a little butterfly is.

23:56.869 --> 24:02.006
-The Monarch butterflies
are special because they
travel really long ways.

24:06.145 --> 24:10.548
WILL SMITH: The Monarch's
don't like winter in Iowa,
they migrate South.

24:19.091 --> 24:25.162
♪ ♪

24:25.565 --> 24:31.001
AUBREY: The butterflies
they go all the way to Mexico.

24:37.209 --> 24:40.511
Like, I don't know where to
go if I were to go to Mexico,

24:40.780 --> 24:42.846
like how do they get there?

24:43.115 --> 24:45.583
It's like a mystery!

24:48.988 --> 24:52.189
WILL SMITH: After
more than 2,000 miles
they've almost reached their

24:52.324 --> 24:55.893
winter home and there's
a welcome party waiting

24:56.929 --> 24:58.696
to greet them.

25:44.610 --> 25:48.078
WILL SMITH: Okay, so this
may just be co-incidental

25:49.916 --> 25:52.383
but the arrival of
the Monarchs has come at the

25:52.518 --> 25:56.186
same time as the Day of
Dead for so long it's

25:56.255 --> 25:58.622
become part of the culture.

26:49.241 --> 26:53.010
WILL SMITH: It's not
just butterflies from
Iowa that travel here,

26:54.313 --> 26:56.914
they're joined
by immigrants from across

26:56.916 --> 27:01.185
the mid-west and
as far north as Canada,

27:04.023 --> 27:07.858
all heading for
refuge in the forests
of central Mexico.

27:39.391 --> 27:43.594
WILL SMITH: It's one of the
greatest homecomings on earth!

27:45.297 --> 27:49.366
Even though every Monarch here
has another home far away,

27:51.871 --> 27:55.338
each one started life on
a milkweed some place like

27:55.374 --> 27:57.875
Beaconsfield, Iowa.

27:59.478 --> 28:03.947
It's hard to know where these
Monarchs belong, Iowa, Mexico,

28:06.318 --> 28:08.719
on the wing or all of those?

28:10.923 --> 28:14.591
These butterflies show that
the earth has no borders.

28:17.430 --> 28:20.163
Everything is interconnected.

28:20.433 --> 28:23.934
It turns out what happens in
Vegas doesn't stay in Vegas!

28:24.937 --> 28:28.839
It's linked to the
rest of the planet.

28:32.478 --> 28:35.779
And on a world where
everything is connected,

28:37.483 --> 28:40.451
the smallest actions can
have global consequences.

28:43.022 --> 28:46.290
Take the plastic
bottles we throw away.

28:48.560 --> 28:51.528
Well, they might just end up
on someone else's doorstep.

29:01.173 --> 29:04.808
This Hermit crab is
looking for a new home.

29:13.652 --> 29:17.554
House hunting is a
especially hard when someone's

29:17.689 --> 29:19.990
trashed your neighborhood.

29:23.429 --> 29:27.331
Millions of tons
of plastic end up in
our oceans each year.

29:32.638 --> 29:35.706
But one guy's trash is
another guy's treasure!

29:45.217 --> 29:51.388
♪ ♪

30:00.499 --> 30:06.203
Hermit crabs have
been found living in
garbage across the planet,

30:06.872 --> 30:10.107
after all a plastic
house can last a long time.

30:21.086 --> 30:25.022
But not every creature can
adapt like the Hermit crab.

30:27.226 --> 30:31.295
As we change our planet
most life on earth
struggles to keep up.

30:35.601 --> 30:37.467
CHRIS: Right now there's
seven and a half billion of us

30:37.603 --> 30:40.437
turning the lights on and
flushing the toilet and

30:40.439 --> 30:42.405
driving our cars and
turning up the heat in our

30:42.441 --> 30:44.975
house and none
of that comes for free.

30:47.813 --> 30:49.946
JEFF: When you look at the
earth from space and you

30:49.949 --> 30:52.215
realize the finiteness
of our planet,

30:52.284 --> 30:54.684
the thinness of
our atmosphere,

30:54.720 --> 30:58.554
it's obvious that the earth,
like any environmental system

30:58.591 --> 31:00.591
has a limited
carrying capacity.

31:02.761 --> 31:05.062
PEGGY: The greatest
threat to our planet,

31:05.064 --> 31:08.765
I think we are probably
the potential greatest
threat to our planet.

31:09.968 --> 31:12.369
WILL SMITH: But there's
hope for us all,

31:12.438 --> 31:15.004
because there's something
else that's changed too,

31:15.808 --> 31:18.942
something that could help
save our precious home!

31:22.932 --> 31:24.764
-Alright, we're gonna roll.

31:25.200 --> 31:27.401
WILL SMITH: Christmas 1968,

31:28.170 --> 31:32.239
an astronaut took
this photograph.

31:32.508 --> 31:36.109
It went viral
when that wasn't such
an easy thing to do

31:36.111 --> 31:39.312
because it was the first
time we'd ever seen a color

31:39.348 --> 31:41.248
portrait of our planet.

31:48.123 --> 31:51.058
-Because little planet Earth
photobombing the moon.

31:59.401 --> 32:01.668
WILL SMITH: It
was a pretty deal,

32:01.737 --> 32:03.837
it showed us how
beautiful our world is,

32:05.007 --> 32:08.108
turns out photos
don't do it justice.

32:11.747 --> 32:13.546
PEGGY: When we look out
the window and we see the

32:13.616 --> 32:16.550
beautiful oceans,
beautiful land masses,

32:18.153 --> 32:21.121
the thin layer of atmosphere
that protects the Earth,

32:22.424 --> 32:27.093
it just really gives you a
sense of how special this

32:27.129 --> 32:30.230
place is where we live.

32:30.466 --> 32:33.967
CHRIS: It's an interesting
coincidence that
at this time in history,

32:34.036 --> 32:36.570
when our population has gotten
so big that we're starting to

32:36.705 --> 32:40.840
make global changes to the
planet it's also the time that

32:40.876 --> 32:44.043
we've invented space flight
which allows us to see the

32:44.079 --> 32:46.813
whole world as one place.

32:51.654 --> 32:54.821
NICOLE: Seeing earth from
space made me think of myself

32:55.958 --> 33:00.127
and everybody else
that I share the planet
with as Earthlings.

33:10.272 --> 33:13.407
♪ ♪

33:33.696 --> 33:38.365
WILL SMITH: All over the world
people love to party and in

33:38.701 --> 33:42.569
India every Spring people
celebrate Mother Earth's new

33:42.704 --> 33:44.404
life in colors.

33:48.343 --> 33:50.243
CHRIS: One of the biggest
changes I noticed within

33:50.245 --> 33:54.915
myself as a result of
flying in space was that the

33:55.050 --> 33:57.684
difference between us
and them disappeared.

34:08.330 --> 34:10.864
-Somehow going around
the world in 92 minutes,

34:10.933 --> 34:14.067
not just once but over
and over and over again,

34:14.069 --> 34:17.771
turned the entire world
into one shared place.

34:23.011 --> 34:26.012
CHRIS: I think it's
a perspective that's
seeps into astronauts.

34:26.048 --> 34:28.148
I think it's a
perspective that's,

34:28.283 --> 34:30.383
that's kind of
good for everybody.

35:10.125 --> 35:12.158
LELAND: I truly believe that
if more people could have the

35:12.227 --> 35:14.995
opportunity to see
the planet from space,

35:15.797 --> 35:18.731
looking at the rich colors,
looking at the fact that there

35:18.767 --> 35:22.702
are no borders separating us
we could see that we are truly

35:22.805 --> 35:25.672
all connected as human beings.

35:30.679 --> 35:33.747
WILL SMITH: Ever been on a
trip and seen something new?

35:34.183 --> 35:38.084
Something incredibly beautiful
or something that changed the

35:38.120 --> 35:40.220
way you think about things.

35:40.823 --> 35:45.091
Now imagine that
trip was to space.

35:45.160 --> 35:48.995
You've seen something
only a very few
people have ever seen.

35:50.165 --> 35:53.900
Astronauts need to tell someone,
anyone, everyone!

35:55.103 --> 35:58.371
Soon they're ready
to go back down but it's
actually bittersweet.

36:00.508 --> 36:03.176
I mean they're
going back to the
place that made them but

36:03.278 --> 36:05.612
leaving the place
that shaped them.

36:08.316 --> 36:10.317
-Last day in space.

36:12.154 --> 36:15.488
After 665 total days over
three different expeditions.

36:18.527 --> 36:21.061
Quite amazing to think
that I'd lived up there,

36:21.196 --> 36:23.897
just under two years of
my life, pretty amazing.

36:26.969 --> 36:29.569
It was hard
to leave because I knew I
wouldn't be coming back.

36:41.049 --> 36:42.816
Jeepers!

36:48.257 --> 36:51.791
But I was so excited
about going back home and,

36:51.827 --> 36:55.095
and being back on
earth having you know,

36:56.398 --> 37:01.034
wind and smelling the air
and just being on earth.

37:04.339 --> 37:07.073
WILL SMITH: But coming
home is not easy.

37:07.943 --> 37:11.945
Mother Earth doesn't
exactly welcome you
back with open arms!

37:21.223 --> 37:26.092
♪ ♪

37:49.751 --> 37:53.753
-We land in Kazakhstan,
there's not many people around

37:53.755 --> 37:57.891
so there's no risk
of us damaging or hurting
anybody during a re-entry.

38:00.128 --> 38:02.429
<i>WOMAN (over radio):</i>
<i>We have maneuver, copy.</i>

38:10.405 --> 38:12.906
CHRIS: The earth's atmosphere
is a protective shield around

38:13.041 --> 38:15.408
our planet, it
keeps our radiation.

38:17.712 --> 38:21.982
It keeps our rocks and
meteorites but it also keeps

38:22.117 --> 38:25.986
out astronauts, suddenly we're
on the other side of that

38:26.121 --> 38:30.090
protective body and we are
essentially an invader.

39:09.531 --> 39:11.831
PEGGY: During re-entry
the window seat is...

39:12.700 --> 39:14.667
It's interesting.

39:17.172 --> 39:19.806
CHRIS: Flying the Russian
(inaudible) is a little bit

39:20.242 --> 39:22.842
like flying a meteorite home.

39:25.847 --> 39:28.381
LELAND: You can look out and
see the orange and purple

39:28.983 --> 39:32.752
flames of 3,000 degrees,
they are this far from you.

39:33.889 --> 39:36.089
That's pretty frickin' scary.

39:37.926 --> 39:40.827
CHRIS: You're going
17,000 miles an hour,

39:40.896 --> 39:44.997
eight kilometers a second and
somehow you have to get rid of

39:45.067 --> 39:47.901
all of that speed, you
have to apply the brakes.

39:50.539 --> 39:55.208
WILL SMITH: Re-entry is about
the most dangerous thing an
astronaut will ever do.

40:05.270 --> 40:08.938
(inaudible rado chatter)

40:12.110 --> 40:15.411
CHRIS: It's an extremely
complex and dangerous
process to return home.

40:17.415 --> 40:20.316
You have to control your
spaceship so you can end up at

40:20.385 --> 40:22.886
the landing point where
everybody's waiting for you.

40:24.890 --> 40:26.789
WILL SMITH: The search and
rescue team doesn't know

40:26.792 --> 40:31.060
exactly where Peggy will fall
back to earth but one things

40:31.062 --> 40:34.297
for certain, gravity will
eventually bring her home.

40:36.034 --> 40:38.334
PEGGY: The Russian's never
design their vehicle to land

40:38.370 --> 40:42.405
on the water so it's always
been a land landing for them

40:42.474 --> 40:45.475
and it works, it's
abrupt but it works.

40:51.816 --> 40:54.383
Once we get inside
the atmosphere,

40:54.419 --> 40:57.253
about five miles above the
planet a parachute will open.

41:02.761 --> 41:04.994
Okay, we're good now.

41:14.973 --> 41:20.677
♪ ♪

41:23.782 --> 41:25.615
(thud)

41:28.153 --> 41:30.320
Most people compare
it to a car crash,

41:30.722 --> 41:33.523
I would compare it to
maybe two car crashes.

41:37.195 --> 41:41.331
When we hit the ground and you
feel everything settle that

41:41.333 --> 41:43.666
was when I knew we
were home again.

42:15.634 --> 42:17.400
-Peggie, welcome back.

42:19.337 --> 42:23.272
PEGGY: It's incredibly
hard to describe how heavy

42:23.341 --> 42:25.808
everything feels in
those first few minutes.

42:27.712 --> 42:29.979
-Just moving your arm
this much is like,

42:30.715 --> 42:34.384
it has to be a huge conscious
effort to move your arm at all

42:36.187 --> 42:39.088
so you're like, "Wow,
space was good!"

42:43.194 --> 42:45.762
Gravity sucks!

42:52.771 --> 42:55.905
WILL SMITH: Peggy hasn't just
looked at space or visited it,

42:56.908 --> 43:01.678
she's lived there, so is
her home back in Iowa?

43:03.081 --> 43:05.615
Or the whole earth?

43:05.617 --> 43:07.917
Or is it up on the ISS?

43:09.054 --> 43:12.956
Truth is, like the
Monarch it's all of them!

43:16.561 --> 43:19.896
-I'm not sure
whether I feel more like an
Earthling or a space woman.

43:22.900 --> 43:25.702
I think being a space
woman's a lot more fun.

43:34.646 --> 43:36.312
LELAND: When I got
home from space,

43:36.414 --> 43:40.382
after getting out of my suit,
then to have a meal without

43:40.785 --> 43:43.252
the food floating away from
you and being able to pet your

43:43.254 --> 43:47.090
dog and talk to your parents
face to face it made me feel

43:48.159 --> 43:50.994
so much more connected
to the planet.

43:53.732 --> 43:56.231
JERRY: You know after
that space experience
being back on the planet

43:56.267 --> 43:59.802
I think what really sky
rocketed me is just gratitude.

44:01.506 --> 44:03.973
You know how good we
have it on the earth.

44:06.678 --> 44:09.412
NICOLE: I couldn't wait to
feel what a breeze would be

44:09.914 --> 44:13.282
like again you, you know what
the smell of grass was gonna

44:13.351 --> 44:16.119
you know smell like again.

44:17.955 --> 44:20.356
CHRIS: It's the smell of
earth, the smell of home,

44:20.859 --> 44:23.692
the smells of the
natural world.

44:23.762 --> 44:25.962
It's over powering, it's
kind of overwhelming.

44:29.000 --> 44:31.100
MAE: Just because you
physically leave the surface

44:31.235 --> 44:33.703
of the earth does not
mean you leave the earth,

44:33.705 --> 44:36.339
because the earth
is part of you.

44:37.375 --> 44:39.642
MIKE: I think we're
pretty special, yeah,

44:39.711 --> 44:42.211
we might be small in
comparison to the rest of that

44:42.213 --> 44:45.714
universe but I dare anybody
from any other planet to come

44:46.384 --> 44:48.817
up with a place
as nice as ours,

44:48.853 --> 44:51.821
I think we definitely have
the nicest home on the block!

44:55.060 --> 44:58.227
JEFF: This is our home,
the earth it's, it's the
only place we've got, it,

44:58.362 --> 45:02.465
it is one strange rock because
it's ours and we are here and

45:02.600 --> 45:05.534
we don't know if any other
place in the universe, yet,

45:05.570 --> 45:08.570
that can support life.

45:09.307 --> 45:12.608
We're very lucky to
have it as our home.

45:16.481 --> 45:17.814
MIKE: There's no
place like home!

45:19.884 --> 45:21.984
CHRIS: There is no
place like home!

45:27.258 --> 45:30.226
PEGGY: There's definitely
no place like home!

45:33.064 --> 45:36.699
WILL SMITH: For thousands of
years maybe tens of thousands

45:37.602 --> 45:40.069
we've looked up and
asked questions.

45:41.106 --> 45:44.040
Now for the first time
in history we have the

45:44.042 --> 45:48.811
opportunity to look down, the
questions are different and so

45:48.946 --> 45:51.180
are the answers.

45:51.716 --> 45:56.953
We can now literally
see how fortunate we are
to call this place home,

45:58.289 --> 46:02.925
it's complex, calibrated,
inter-connected...

46:04.028 --> 46:06.863
fine-tuned but fragile.

46:09.066 --> 46:11.667
Perspective is everything.

46:11.936 --> 46:15.137
From down here earth
is simply our home.

46:15.640 --> 46:19.575
From up there, it
is one strange rock.

46:29.454 --> 46:34.056
♪ ♪

46:34.325 --> 46:35.424
-I miss space!

46:35.493 --> 46:36.692
-What did you say?

46:36.728 --> 46:40.429
-You can ask me when I'm
95 do I wanna go back.

46:40.698 --> 46:41.763
-I love it!

46:41.799 --> 46:43.566
-The answer would
absolutely be yes!

46:43.635 --> 46:45.501
-I wanna go back!

46:45.636 --> 46:47.036
Don't tell my wife!

46:47.105 --> 46:48.504
(laughs).

46:48.506 --> 46:50.439
Don't put that on television!

